spans.text: Ill-brooked the generous Spirit , in those days When Learning was the certain road to praise , When Nobles , with a love of Science blessed , Approved in others what themselves possessed
those labours , which our Fathers bore That Crown withheld , which They in triumph wore
Where Merit and Reward went hand in hand
Where Heroes , Parentlike , the Poet viewed ? — By whom they saw their glorious deeds renewed
her blessings , which GOD meant for all
to love the Virtue of a foe
controlment speak In guilty blushes on the villain's cheek
the Muse , who feared not Law
one dull drowsy track of business
not Truth , as Truth , if told in rhyme ?

( the worst of curses Heaven can send ) To have a foe , too proud to have a friend , Erring by form , which Blockheads sacred hold , Never making new faults , and never mending old , Rebukes my Spirit , bids the daring Muse Subjects more equal to her weakness choose ; Bids her frequent the haunts of humble swains , Nor dare to traffic in ambitious strains ; Bids her , indulging the poetic whim In quaint-wrought Ode , or Sonnet pertly trim , Along the Churchway path complain with GREY , Or dance with MASON on the first of May ?

The generous ardour of the Muse
from the vengeance of a Scribbler's pen
bring their vices to the public ear
not the honest blood of humble swains Quick as the tide which swells a Monarch's veins
who wealth and titles can bestow
her Love , Act as thy Birth demands
thy worthy Father taught , Who earned those Honours
The sight of such a Son would blast his eyes
more , with shame and sorrow , amongst the dead In endless night to hide his reverend head

thee more Than ever King a scoundrel made before , Nay , to allow thy pride a deeper spring , Though God in vengeance had made Thee a King , Taking on Virtue's wing her daring flight , The Muse should drag thee trembling to the light , Probe thy foul wounds
thy bosom bare To the keen question of the searching air
the titled slave , Who smarts beneath the stroke which Satire gave
Striving to hide the feelings of his heart
pay regard To the wild ravings of a frantic bard
of Conscience , which good men secures From all those evil moments guilt endures
with discretion fraught , " Is all her malice
Nor would I wish to stop that harmless dart " Which plays around
Dissembling Wretch ! hence to the Stoic school , And there amongst thy brethren play the fool , There , unrebuked
a Man , whom SATIRE cannot reach
his conscience ripped with steady eye
from the moment of his birth
Those actions , which he blushed not to commit
villain pale ? why bends his eye Inward , abashed , when MURPHY
He shifts his sails , and catches every wind
With laurelled wreaths the flatterer's brows adorn , Bid Virtue crouch , bid Vice exalt her horn , Bid Cowards thrive , put honesty to flight
the inmost closet of my heart
Pay him but well , and MURPHY is thy friend
Vice no longer rains down showers of gold

each man of nice and juster
Shunning his steps , decrees , by Honour taught
stoops so low To be the base betrayer of a foe

most glaring contraries unite , And prove , beyond dispute , that black is white , To make firm Honour tamely league with shame , Make Vice and Virtue differ but in name , To prove that Chains and Freedom are but one , That to be saved must mean to be undone , Is there not GUTHRIE
call All Opposites to proof , and conquer all
